#### <span id="iv.v.viii.i-p0.1"></span>Chapter I.

<span id="iv.v.viii.i-p1"></span>Of the vigils which we endured.

<span id="iv.v.viii.i-p2"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="iv.v.viii.i-p2.1"></span>When</span> then the previous Conference
was ended, and the intervening silence of night as well, as we had been
conducted by the holy Abbot Joseph to a separate cell for the sake of
quiet, but had passed the whole night without sleep (since owing to his
words a fire was raging in our hearts), we came forth from the cell and
retired about a hundred yards from it and sat down in a secluded spot.
And so as an opportunity was given by the shades of night for secret and
familiar converse together, as we sat there Abbot Germanus groaned
heavily.

